Wash and dry all produce. In a #small pot{}, bring @water{1 1/2%cups} and 
@Veggie Stock Concentrate{1} to a boil. Core, seed, and remove white ribs from 
@Red Bell Pepper{1}(cored and seeded), then finely dice. Mince @Jalapeño{1}(minced, 
ribs and seeds removed for less heat). Drain half the @Corn{1%can} and half the 
@Black Beans{1%box} from their containers (use the rest as you like). Rinse 
black beans.

Once stock is boiling, add @Quinoa{3/4%cup}. Cover and reduce to a low simmer. 
Cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Heat a #medium pan{} over medium heat. Add @Pepitas{1%ounce} and toast in pan 
until they are lightly browned and smell nutty, ~{2-3%minutes}, stirring 
frequently. Remove from pan and set aside.

> If pepitas seem like they might burn, immediately remove pan from heat.

Add drained corn, jalapeño (to taste), and a drizzle of @Olive Oil{2%teaspoon} to 
same pan over medium-high heat. Cook until lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}, 
tossing. During the last minute or two, add drained black beans to warm through. 
Season to taste with @Salt{to taste} and @Pepper{to taste}.

Roughly chop @Cilantro{1/4%ounce}(roughly chopped). Cut @Lime{1} into halves. In 
a #small bowl{}, whisk together juice from half the lime, @Cumin{2%teaspoon}, 
and @Olive Oil{1%tbsp}.

Fluff quinoa with a fork. In a #large bowl{}, toss quinoa, corn mixture, bell 
pepper, cilantro, and dressing. Season generously with salt and pepper. Divide 
between plates and sprinkle with pepitas and @Feta Cheese{1/2%cup}.

> Quinoa pairs well with Southwestern flavors: black beans, corn, jalapeño, and 
pepitas. The dressing with cumin and lime adds a zesty, citrusy touch with 
earthy undertones. Plus, it's packed with protein and vitamin C to help 
supercharge you through your day.